Q9: It’s getting better and growing bigger. More people are opening up to the idea of Studying and working in the arts. Funding is always a problem, but it can give us the opportunity to think collectively, sustainably about our practices and it’s position in the ecosystem of the city, about the arts role as the ‘alternative’ (by this i mean a way of departing and challenging norms for everyone, not just the perception that the route of the arts is just another choice, one that is undeniably privilege coloured)

Q9: It is definitely growing with an increasing amount of opportunities, in part due to the government's funding in specific /ahem/ areas of the arts. However, I'd say a huge problem for local aspiring artists is actually the fact that most Singaporeans don't care enough about the local arts scene, very much due to the lack of arts appreciation because of the general idea of " the path to success"(ugh) and the failure of the education system in teaching our young the importance of arts and culture (which i think/hope is slowly getting better). So even if there are more opportunities now for local artists, most are unable to sustain them simply because there isn't enough demand out there. Of course this is a problem that requires long-term solutions, but giving artists more platforms to reach out to a wider, more diverse audience is definitely the way to go in the short run, especially targeting the youths cos the current generation of students right now are going to be become future parents right). So yes, more accessible platforms to showcase local artist(e)s, and it'd be even better if you could also shine a spotlight on genres that are less seen, and give them a platform to explain why they do what they do.
